Germany: A Budget Fetish That Costs a Lot
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It was actually Germany that insisted on this principle being incorporated into the criteria set out in the Maastricht Treaty, which establish the conditions for membership of the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a change in political regime.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France, during the referendum on ratification of the Maastricht Treaty, in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, on the other hand, it has become commonplace, so to speak, to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months now, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schäuble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes central bank independence.
If he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price norm," in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nevertheless offers his advice on the tools the ECB should use and on how it should use them to achieve such a goal.
We know of precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Germany's Finance Minister, gave his advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was ultimately to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with typically Dutch brevity, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician expressing his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, it was absolutely unusual). "Yet," he added, "it would be entirely abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account."
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes central bank independence.
Respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of German Stabilitätkultur ("culture of stability").
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to the exhortations of Chancellor Konrad Adenauer, who wanted it to contain the rise in interest rates, in 1956.
At that time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was on the verge of creating the Fifth Republic, with a French Bank that reported to the Minister of Finance.
But it was a different time.
Following the various crises that have shaken the EMU, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Has the old doctrine become obsolete?
Europe remains very vulnerable; the median inhabitant of the EMU has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming, we are close to a critical situation.
The United States, nevertheless, do better.
Despite a politically difficult blockage to manage, they managed to tackle the macroeconomic problem (weak aggregate demand) they were facing by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which, at first, were much more severe than in Europe.
There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the more capable they are of fulfilling their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of support from the population.
And indeed, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, particularly in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to greater pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy comes from the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto compelled to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course and allow the economy to fall into stagnation, or worse).
The political outcome of this chain of events is a very clear regression toward nationalism, from the right as well as the left, in all EMU countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany is leading the way, with its obsession with the schwarze Null, with fiscal balance, come what may.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably, not only from an arithmetic perspective but also from a moral standpoint, even though this defies economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
By the end of the nineteenth century, the leading German experts on public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures should be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public expenditures, and the resources they require, are justified by their usefulness.
This means that investments aimed at improving productivity—equipment expenditures—can be financed with debt, the servicing of which is ensured by the growth of incomes and the tax base associated with them.
This classical approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
It is crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment expenditures are managed at this level (a proportion that has been decreasing, as the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with the support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (mittelstand).
But compared to the early 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenditures have decreased by about 15%.
For more than a decade, they have been insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how one prepares for the future, this is how one undermines productivity and prosperity.
In short, the schwarze Null goes against the intended goal.
The aging infrastructure (certainly not as bad as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the fiscal frugality of German leaders extends beyond Germany's borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which does not have exchange rates to adapt to national particularities.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But turning the only institution willing to "do what needs to be done" to get the EMU back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
That states use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have available to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain degree of maneuverability in this regard.
